&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]Professor Emma Smith (WSC077)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]This 
[normal]submission
[normal] 
[normal]presents a summary of recent research findings into 
[normal]gendered patterns of participation in post-compulsory 
[normal]STEM 
[normal]education
[normal] in the UK
[normal]. It examines the trajectory of learning which takes students from A-level qualifications, through undergraduate work and into 
[normal]early 
[normal]employment or further study. It also takes a 
[normal]long term view 
[normal]to 
[normal]monitor participation and attainment over an extended period of time.
[normal] The findings suggest that almost three decades of initiatives to increase participation in STEM subjects have had little noticeable impact on the recruitment data and g
[normal]endered patterns of participation persist in several subject areas. 
[normal]This is despite more women entering HE and little gender difference in the entry qualifications for STEM subjects.
[normal] 
[normal]While more women are studying science, as broadly conceived, than ever be
[normal]fore; 
[normal]recruitment to key areas, namely physics and engineering remains stagnant.
[normal] 
[normal]However for those women who do remain in 
[normal]the ‘science stream’, patterns of employment in graduate careers and further study appear relatively equitable
[normal] for most of the main su
[normal]bject groups, however concerns 
[normal]about early employment trajectories
[normal] among the engineering and computer sciences are still apparent.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Data is presented on
[normal] 
[normal]long term
[normal] trends in 
[normal]the 
[normal]participation
[normal] of men and women
[normal] in post-compulsory science
[normal] 
[normal]programmes. The datasets used for this analysis are of the highest quality available and they represent many hundreds of thousands of individuals
[normal] (see appendix for further information on the datasets used)
[normal]. They enable us to take a long term view on how 
[normal]th
[normal]e 
[normal]participation of male and female students in post-compulsory STEM subjects has been shaped by an expanding HE sector and allow us to evaluate the long term impact of policies and initiatives which have aimed to encourage more young women, in particular, 
[normal]to study the sciences. 
[normal]The results presented here span three phases of post-compulsory STEM training: attainment at A-level, uptake of STEM subjects at undergraduate level and the 
[normal]early
[normal] career destinations of recent STEM graduates.
[normal] They address the followi
[normal]ng research questions:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1 Participation
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]A consideration of long term trends in participation in 
[normal]A-level
[normal] pure science courses (biology, chemistry and physics) suggests that not one of these subjects appears
[normal] to be thriving. In physics there are now fewer male students studying the subject than in the 1960s, with numbers in decline since the early 1990s (Graph
[normal] 1). The stability in the female participation figures comes despite initiatives (such as 
[normal]GIST and WISE)
[normal] that focus on encouraging girls to study physics after the age of 16. While t
[normal]here is no evidence
[normal] to suggest
[normal] that female candidates are being turned awa
[normal]y from 
[normal]studying A-level physics
[normal] in greater numbers
[normal] 
[normal]than previously,
[normal] there is nothing to suggest that 
[normal]these 
[normal]initiatives have had a notably positive effect on recruitment either.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Graph 1: Participation in A-level physics, male and female candidates 1961-20[bold]11[bold]Source: DES, DfES, DCSF, QCA, JCQ, AQA, Edexcel, IoP
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Until relatively recently A-level chemistry was a male dominated subject (Graph 2). From the early 1990s there has been a gradual narrowing of th
[normal]e participation gap
[normal]. This has
[normal] largely been due to a decline in the number of male candidates
[normal], although numbers are starting to increase. 
[normal]The introduction of compulsory science 
[normal]in the late 1980s
[normal] 
[normal]appears in itself to have 
[normal]had no noticeable impact on A-level recruitment to chemistry, for
[normal] either 
[normal]men or women
[normal]. 
[normal]Although w
[normal]e have seen a steady feminisation of the
[normal] subject to the extent to which, at present, 
[normal]participation in A-level 
[normal]c
[normal]hemistry is 
[normal]largely
[normal] gender neutral.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Graph 2: Participation in A-level chemistry, male[bold] and female candidates 1961-2011[bold]Source: DES, DfES, DCSF, QCA, JCQ, AQA, Edexcel, IoP
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2 
[normal]Attainment 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In order to examine how 
[normal]gendered 
[normal]patterns of attainment 
[normal]have
[normal] varied over the history of the A-level we examined changes in the
[normal] relative attainment of male and female students at A-level grade C or higher
[normal]. What this historical 
[normal]overview
[normal] shows is that the 
[normal]gender achievement gap 
[normal]in the pure sciences has hardly varied over the last five decades providing no evidence that male student
[normal]s have ever outperformed females at this level
[normal].
[normal] For example, in physics 
[normal]there has been some shifting of the achievement gap in favour of female candidates
[normal] s
[normal]ince the 
[normal]mid
[normal]-
[normal]1990s
[normal] (Graph 3).
[normal] 
[normal]However the 
[normal]gap is negligible and overall it can be said that attainme
[normal]nt at the higher grade levels is gender neutral.
[normal] The same is true for chemistry. U
[normal]ntil the late 1990s 
[normal]there was no difference in the proportion of male and female candidates achieving a grade C or higher in A-level chemistry, m
[normal]ore recently the achievement 
[normal]gap has 
[normal]moved to be slightly
[normal] in favour of female candidates. 
[normal]As with physics, t
[normal]his appears to coincide with 
[normal]a 
[normal]decline in the number of men entered for the subject
[normal], which may suggest that c
[normal]hemistry is losing some of its higher attaining male entrants. However, the achievement gap between 
[normal]men and women
[normal] is still relatively small suggesting that 
[normal]attainment in c
[normal]hemistry
[normal] at 
[normal]this level
[normal] is gender neutral.
[normal]A positive value indicates overall higher achievement among female candidates
[normal]. Values of less than 4% are not considered to represent a noticeable gap
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1 
[normal]The expansion of the UK Higher Education system over the last twenty years or so is reflected in a quadrupling of the number of candidates offered places to study
[normal] at undergraduate level
[normal]. 
[normal]This
[normal] increase is particularly apparent among previously under-represented groups: i
[normal]n 1986, 47,696 women accepted places on UCCA and PCAS-administered HND and 
[normal]first 
[normal]degree programmes; b
[normal]y 20
[normal]12
[normal] this had risen to
[normal] over
[normal] 2
[normal]25
[normal],0
[normal]00
[normal]. The early 1990s saw the end of long e
[normal]stablished trends of 
[normal]HE
[normal] courses recruiting more male candidates. Now more female candidates 
[normal]apply and are accepted, a rate of increase since 1994 which has been faster than that for men (Graph 
[normal]4
[normal]).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Graph [bold]4[bold]: Male and f[bold]emale [bold]home [bold]acceptances to all [bold]first [bold]de[bold]gr[bold]ee and HND programmes, 1986-20[bold]1[bold]2[bold]4.2 
[normal]Since 1986, the 
[normal]different 
[normal]STEM 
[normal]subject groups
[normal] have tended to recruit a steady share of female candidates with rates only varying by around 1-2 percentage points. For example, in 1986 5% of 
[normal]all places accepted by female candidates were in the Physical Sciences, this has varied only slightly in the intervening years, although currently the trend is towards a slightly lower share 
[normal](3%) 
[normal]of female candidates who are accepted to study this group of
[normal] subjects. 
[normal]Almost half of all places on STEM undergraduate courses are now taken by women, a proportion which, as Graph 5 shows, has steadily increased since 1986 and is in line with the increasing numbers of women studying at university. 
[normal]While this sugges
[normal]ts that a relatively large and stable proportion of women do wish to study science (as broadly conceived), 
[normal]gender stereotyped patterns of subject choice still persist
[normal] - over 50% of candidates studying 
[normal]the 
[normal]b
[normal]iological and 
[normal]medical s
[normal]ciences 
[normal]are female
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]while 
[normal]the proportion o
[normal]f female students studying the engineering s
[normal]ciences has hardly varied over the period considered
[normal] (Graph 5)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Graph 5[bold]: Proportion of candidates accepted to main STEM subject groups who are female, 1986-[bold]2011[bold]&#xa0;
