[normal].2
[normal] Well over half of engineering science students who enter employment remain in the field, indeed by far the largest recruiter of engineering graduates are the engineering 
[normal]professional occupations (civil engineers, production engineers and so on). However, this is an area where gender stereotypes patterns of participation persist and to some extent they remain when female engineers leave education and enter the workforce, es
[normal]pecially when the proportions who enter professional occupations is considered. Gende
[normal]red recruitment patterns among m
[normal]athematical s
[normal]cience graduates are relatively slight
[normal] with a
[normal] large proportion of these graduates who enter employment work
[normal]ing
[normal] in the 
[normal]business
[normal] and f
[normal]inance 
[normal]sector
[normal]. Having a computer science degree, 
[normal]o
[normal]n the other hand, appears to be more of an advantage for men, in terms of entry to graduate professions – note in particular that almost 30% of female computer science graduates are in relatively unsk
[normal]illed jobs six months after graduation. This later trend is one that exists to a certain degree between men and women in each of the three subject areas considered here.
