[normal]6.1 
[normal]This 
[normal]submission has presented findings from recent and on-going research projects that have tracked the
[normal] gendered patterns of partic
[normal]i
[normal]pation
[normal] 
[normal]in STEM-related 
[normal]post-compulsory education
[normal] in the UK
[normal]. It has examined the trajectory of learning which takes students from A-level qualifications, through undergraduate work and into employment or further study. As well as looking at how levels of engagemen
[normal]t between men and women var
[normal]y at each stage
[normal], the research reported here has also taken a long term view and considered the best available evidence to monitor participation and attainment over
[normal] an extended period of
[normal] time.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2 D
[normal]espite 
[normal]many years of 
[normal]initiatives 
[normal]to encourage more women into STEM education and careers
[normal], 
[normal]women
[normal] 
[normal]remain under-represented 
[normal]in
[normal] many parts of
[normal] the field 
[normal]and as the
[normal] results presented here show
[normal], levels of unequal participation in key STEM subjects have varied little over the last twe
[normal]nty five years. T
[normal]h
[normal]is is despite more
[normal] women
[normal] entering HE and little 
[normal]gender 
[normal]difference in 
[normal]the entry
[normal] qualifications
[normal] 
[normal]for
[normal] STEM subjects
[normal]. So i
[normal]f qualification is not a barrier
[normal] to participation, then why ha
[normal]ve
[normal] the 
[normal]increased number of women studying in HE not
[normal] been 
[normal]reflected in
[normal] subjects such as physics and engineering?
[normal] The answer according to much of the literature in this area 
[normal]appears to
[normal] lie in the various socio-cultural barriers 
[normal]to 
[normal]STEM 
[normal]education
[normal] 
[normal]which women experience. 
[normal]Indeed
[normal] t
[normal]he data presented here 
[normal]shows
[normal] that wom
[normal]en are engaged with science and wish to study the subject at t
[normal]he
[normal] highest levels. 
[normal]Rather
[normal], the types of science 
[normal]subjects
[normal] they study, and p
[normal]sychology is a notable example here, are not
[normal] necessarily
[normal] t
[normal]hose
[normal] which policy makers and employers 
[normal]consider to be the ‘
[normal]str
[normal]ategic, important 
[normal]and
[normal] vulnerable
[normal]’ science
[normal] 
[normal]subject
[normal]s.
[normal] 
[normal]Women are 
[normal]also 
[normal]studying 
[normal]many 
[normal]science 
[normal]subject
[normal]s in higher numbers tha
[normal]n previously
[normal] 
[normal]and
[normal] yet recruitment to
[normal] subjects such as
[normal] physics and engineering remains stagnant.
[normal] This may be a reflection of the critical mass 
[normal]model which suggests that female recruitment to these subjects is still too low to
[normal] 
[normal]be
[normal] 
[normal]self-sustaining
[normal] 
[normal]and generate future growth. However,
[normal] 
[normal]it is 
[normal]importa
[normal]n
[normal]t to remember that numbers of m
[normal]ale participants in 
[normal]physi
[normal]cs
[normal] and engineering subjects
[normal] are 
[normal]also stable.
[normal] 
[normal]In addition,
[normal] f
[normal]or women who do
[normal] remain in the ‘
[normal]STEM
[normal] 
[normal]pipeline
[normal]’, patterns of employment in graduate careers and further study appear relatively equitable: over half of all chemistry and physics
[normal] graduates (male and female) who enter employment remain in the field and similar proportions engage in further study.
[normal] 
[normal]However there are some notable exceptions, especially among the engineering and computer sciences where 
[normal]in the later subject, relatively 
[normal]high proportions of graduates are unemployed or undertaking relatively low skilled jobs.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.3 
[normal]It is very difficult to provide policy recommendations that will easily remedy inequalities in the numbers of women who participate in physics
[normal],
[normal] engineering
[normal] and co
[normal]mputer science
[normal] in HE. Decades of well-funded and well-targeted initiatives have had limited impact and even mak
[normal]ing all young people study the sciences 
[normal]up to the age of 16 had little long term 
[normal]effect 
[normal]on recruitment 
[normal]at the next educational level
[normal]s
[normal]. 
[normal]As male an
[normal]d female students achieve at similar levels in gateway qualification
[normal]s
[normal], there is limited evidence that attainment is a barrier to participation and 
[normal]for women who do study these shortage subjects evidence suggests that many are likely to remain in the field 
[normal]upon graduation. Whatever socio-cultural barriers 
[normal]are preventing the recent expansion of the HE system being reflected in female participation in physics and engineering, they 
[normal]appear to also apply to men
[normal], to some extent,
[normal] and 
[normal]seem
[normal] largely unaffected by gend
[normal]er
[normal]-
[normal]related widening participation initiatives.
