[normal]Appendi[bold]ces[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]A1 [bold]Sources of data[bold]A1.1 Post-compulsory schooling: data were obtained electronically and as hard copy from a number of government departments and other official organisations, including the Department for Children, Schools and Families (and its predecessors the Department fo
[normal]r Education and Skills and Department for Education and Science), the former Qualifications and Curriculum Authority, the Joint Council for Qualification, the Institute of Physics and the 
[normal]Assessment and Qualifications Alliance
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]A1.2 Higher Education: D
[normal]ata
[normal] retrieved from the Universities Central Admissions Service (UCAS) 
[normal]were used to investigate patterns of participation in STEM first degree and Higher National Diploma programmes at UK universities. 
[normal]A1.3 Graduate destinations: Data on participation in furt
[normal]her study and employment destinations were retrieved from the Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA). Analysis of the UCAS data shows that the majority of STEM graduates are UK-domiciled, full-time students, so the focus here was limited to this group. 
[normal]The HESA first destination survey gathers information on the activities of graduates six months after they leave university. Response rates tend to be relatively high: for the Physical Sciences they are over 80%. It is recognised that this dataset only con
[normal]siders destinations six months after the student has left university and that career trajectories may be very different in the subsequent period. However, it tells us a great deal about the sorts of jobs that are available to science graduates.
